This paper deals with the existence and size of well-supported approximate Nash equilibria in win-lose bimatrix games, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The paper also uses graph-theoretic concepts and constructions (cs.DS) to prove some of its results. Additionally, the paper involves the analysis of computational complexity and the existence of equilibria (cs.CC), as well as the use of algorithms and optimization techniques (cs.AI) to construct examples of games that require larger supports. Finally, the paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in its analysis of the payoff guarantees of different equilibria.
